In article <73819@cup.portal.com> Christopher_C_Lapp@cup.portal.com writes:
>Plaintext encryption has made it impossible to passively 
>monitor an adversary and hope to gain any  true  
>information.  What, then, should an intelligence agency do 
>to defend against the plaintext threat?  Simple--end the 
>passive and centralized approach to information gathering.

Thank you, Mr. Lapp, for solving this dilemma.  After you introduced us to
your totally impenetrable scheme of semantic plaintext encryption, I was in
deep despair for the security of our nation.  Now though, I rest assured
that the world is once again safe for democracy.

